			<td class="xar-norm message">
				<div class="xarbb-messagecontrols">
					<div class="leftnote"><span class="xar-sub">Posted:Jan 15, 2015 5:48:57 PM</span></div>
					<div class="rightnote">
											</div>
					<div style="float:left;"><strong class="xar-sub">Subject:<a name="92080" href="http://www.ldonline.org/xarbb/topic/14007#92080">Re:  Re:  I so Desperately need info on Speed Processing
</a></strong></div>
					<div style="clear: both;"></div>
				</div>
				<div style="clear: left;">
															<p>I'd like to respond to this thread with some of my findings.</p>
<p>A few months ago my mood, memory, and cognitive functioning had deteriorated so badly that, without light, I was confused which door I needed to use to enter my bedroom in a house I had lived in nearly all my life. I spent most of each day in bed watching videos or reading stupid things on the Internet. Since then I have been on a gluten-free and casein-free diet as well as omega3 and I'm now a vaguely normal person again although I'm about to start working with a nutritionist with experience with autism to hopefully make further improvements as I'm aware of a number of further digestive issues that aren't as they should be.</p>
<p>I have been tracking myself over time using a processing speed test that you can find here:<br />
<a href="http://www.brainhq.com/#assessment/hack_my_brain" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.brainhq.com/#assessment/hack_my_brain</a></p>
<p>At my worst I was scoring 1st centile in both the tests. I also did an IQ test on lumosity and scored 86. A WAIS test I had myself assessed for in 2011 found my IQ to be 111. So that's a startling drop there although unfortunately they aren't the same IQ tests.</p>
<p>Now I'm 77th centile on the first processing speed test from BrainHQ and 25th centile on the second. This jump to 77th centile sounds very dramatic but I think the nature of that test is that a small difference can make a big difference so perhaps it is not so exciting. It is the improvement in the second test, despite being a smaller percentile improvement, I find more exciting.</p>
<p>There's been a lot of research done on GFCF diets and most of the studies show positive things. Despite this scientific consensus wasn't satisfied as two separate meta-analyses showed methodological flaws in the studies finding positive results. This wikip page talks about that<br />
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gluten-free,_casein-free_diet#Effectiveness" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gluten-free,_casein-free_diet#Effectiveness</a></p>
<p>In 2010 there was a really rigorous study basically designed to put the issue to bed:<br />
<a href="http://www.urmc.rochester.edu/news/story/index.cfm?id=2860" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">http://www.urmc.rochester.edu/news/story/index.cfm?id=2860</a></p>
<p>This study showed no benefit. So end of story, don't bother it is a waste of time, right? Wrong. Due to the way the study was designed children were only gluten and casein free for 4 weeks before they were being given these special cookies that could either contain gluten, casein, both, or neither (administered weekly). This means that the maximum guaranteed amount of time a kid was on the diet was only four weeks and nearly all the studies that show positive improvement were over a much longer period of time many lasting years. All this really proves is that a little bit of gluten or casein--each cookie contained only 20gs--is enough to scupper any chance of benefits so if you do it you have to be strict.</p>
<p>My experience was of slowly seeing an improvement, which I believe is still happening. Additionally I have been on and off omega3 and have concluded beyond all personal doubt that I am quite ill if I am doing GFCF without omega3. So for me the only real positive benefit is when I do GFCF with omega3 as well. GFCF was alone seems to be enough for me to have properly formed stools but without omega3 I started to develop joint pain and I had no energy and a very negative mood: irritability, depression, anxiety, and panic (basically a living hell). Note however that normal diet without omega3 also left me fairly poor mood, low energy, but also all the cognitive impairments.</p>
<p>Basically if you or your child have slow processing speed and any sign of digestive issues I would seriously consider trying GFCF diet with omega3. That said your mileage my vary. My belief now understanding of autism now is that has a strong biomedical basis but can take many forms i.e. there are any number of things that may be wrong. For instance you may not need the omega3 or maybe need something else, or several things. Some companies now offer tests for different things that you can use to find out what steps will be useful. If you do find the right things you can bet you will see improvements beyond just processing speed.</p>
<p>I don't think I can link to anyone here without seeming like I'm promoting but if you google for biomedical autism intervention you should find things.<br />
[Modified by: squeeg on January 16, 2015 04:03 AM]<br />
</p>
																				</div>
			</td>
